<font color="#FF0000">THINGS THAT HAUNT YOU LATER.</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan 16 20:27:59 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Doc Del,<br><br>
Thanks much for this thread, and your posts.  I almost posted yesterday, but didn't due to technical problems.  It's just as well, because I almost said I'd pull my Vietnam experience off my resume because it might influence someone.  Upon thinking about it, I'll leave it on.  If it were to influence someone, I probably would not want to work this them anyway.<br><br>
I had a discussion with another of our posters a few days ago, and discussed a rather touchy subject.  In all our experiences, there were things which happened which make us uncomfortable.  I'm going to post a portion of me e-mail for you guys to see, and perhaps comment upon. Some comes form my diary:<br><br>
&quot;November 3, 1970<br><br>
&quot;'...Two things I've noticed about rescue here.  One is prejudice against the Vietnamese (&quot;Zips&quot;).  The other is hypocracy about our mission here.  (A Marine BUFF went down, and the H-43 was told to stay clear of the area because it was in the way of the UH1H's.  Pilot didn't resist.  Second, the 37th was called upon to help rescue Vietnamese during the flood, and declined.  A hundred people died and thousands are homeless.'<br><br>
&quot;We were a rescue organization, yet we declined a rescue mission which would have saved many people.  There was a typhoon, and much flooding.  We did not help.  <br><br>
&quot;'November 12, 1970<br><br>
&quot;'Smitty was saying that its a bit embarrasing that we didn't go out during the floods a while back and make some pickups.  We could easily have.  In another respect, though, our primary mission is to save downed aircrew members.'<br><br>
&quot;I was rationalizing in that last statement.  Most of us wanted to go out and pull people out of the water.  We couldn't, because the bureacracy did not recognize our greater mission, to win the hearts and minds of the people.  What better way than to pull them out of the water, with us actually going in to get them if necessary?  We were trained and equipped to do so.  Just a few months prior my mission had been Apollo rescue, and we were trained and equipped to go in and get the Apollo 13 astronauts if necessary (as you know, they landed beside the Navy in the wrong ocean for me to participate)...<br><br>
&quot;Because of these situations, we both were uniquely molded into individuals who are not the same as we would have been.  I now have an intolerance to bureaucratic decisions which hurt people...<br><br>
&quot;...(had) our unit (which was already highly decorated) decided to act that day, we probably could have saved at least a dozen lives.  Who knows what changes in the profiles of behaviors that would have brought about.  From what I know of chaos theory, it is totally possible that our lack of will to do those rescues could have made a critical difference in the outcome of some cricical people, and perhaps influenced the outcome of the entire war effort in doing so.&quot;<br>

<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


